00:07:47.390 --> 00:07:51.326
Let me give a bit of context
which involves some statistics.

00:07:51.326 --> 00:07:53.450
I've told you there are 65
million people displaced

00:07:53.450 --> 00:07:56.830
from their homes by
conflict and disaster.

00:07:56.830 --> 00:08:00.680
But the idea I want you to hold
on to through the statistics

00:08:00.680 --> 00:08:03.110
is that we've got a refugee
crisis not just because

00:08:03.110 --> 00:08:06.080
of the number of people
involved but because

00:08:06.080 --> 00:08:08.714
of the nature of
the crisis itself,

00:08:08.714 --> 00:08:10.130
and that nature
goes to the issues

00:08:10.130 --> 00:08:13.970
of the length of displacement,
the location of displacement

00:08:13.970 --> 00:08:15.020
as well.

00:08:15.020 --> 00:08:18.315
So just three things
really-- first of all,

00:08:18.315 --> 00:08:19.190
it's hard to measure.

00:08:19.190 --> 00:08:22.040
But we think-- the UN thinks--

00:08:22.040 --> 00:08:25.610
that the average length of
displacement for a refugee

00:08:25.610 --> 00:08:27.590
is 10 years.

00:08:27.590 --> 00:08:29.780
So you're out of your
own country for 10 years.

00:08:29.780 --> 00:08:32.650
But once you've been out of
your own country for five years,

00:08:32.650 --> 00:08:36.460
the average displacement
goes up to 21 years.

00:08:36.460 --> 00:08:41.320
So hold onto the idea that we're
in a wholly new world where

00:08:41.320 --> 00:08:43.607
the job of public
policy of citizens

00:08:43.607 --> 00:08:45.065
is not just to keep
refugees alive.

00:08:45.065 --> 00:08:47.589
Remember, the Second World
War went on for six years.

00:08:47.589 --> 00:08:49.380
The job is not just to
keep people alive so

00:08:49.380 --> 00:08:51.299
that they can then go home.

00:08:51.299 --> 00:08:53.590
The likelihood is is that
they're not going to go home.

00:08:53.590 --> 00:08:56.620
Because the Civil
War in Afghanistan

00:08:56.620 --> 00:08:59.770
has effectively been
going on since 1979.

00:08:59.770 --> 00:09:01.870
The war in Somalia has
effectively been going on

00:09:01.870 --> 00:09:03.370
since the early 1990s.

00:09:03.370 --> 00:09:05.590
The wars in the Congo have
been effectively going

00:09:05.590 --> 00:09:08.600
on for 30 or 40 years.

00:09:08.600 --> 00:09:12.160
The outlier is the
Lebanese Civil War,

00:09:12.160 --> 00:09:15.940
which lasted 15 years
but then ended in 1990.

00:09:15.940 --> 00:09:18.520
And frankly, Lebanon
is as good as it gets

00:09:18.520 --> 00:09:21.580
for restoring fragile peace.

00:09:21.580 --> 00:09:25.960
But the more likely scenario
is that these fragile states

00:09:25.960 --> 00:09:30.070
are marked by recurrent wars
rather than wars that end.

00:09:30.070 --> 00:09:32.470
So the first point is the
length of displacement changes

00:09:32.470 --> 00:09:33.053
the challenge.

00:09:33.053 --> 00:09:36.240
Secondly, most refugees
are not in refugee camps.

00:09:36.240 --> 00:09:39.190
I get often asked, oh, you
must work in refugee camps,

00:09:39.190 --> 00:09:40.150
and we do.

00:09:40.150 --> 00:09:42.920
But 60% of the world's
refugees are in urban areas,

00:09:42.920 --> 00:09:43.990
not in camps.

00:09:43.990 --> 00:09:46.390
So again, it changes the game.

00:09:46.390 --> 00:09:48.520
The perils are different,
but the possibilities

00:09:48.520 --> 00:09:51.610
are different if you're
living in an urban area rather

00:09:51.610 --> 00:09:53.767
than a refugee camp.

00:09:53.767 --> 00:09:55.600
There are four million
refugees more or less

00:09:55.600 --> 00:10:00.430
in camps, almost all of
them in sub-Saharan Africa.

00:10:00.430 --> 00:10:03.670
The third thing, I think,
is really important--

00:10:03.670 --> 00:10:06.190
is that you'd think
from the media coverage

00:10:06.190 --> 00:10:09.530
that most refugees are in
rich countries like this one.

00:10:09.530 --> 00:10:12.220
But the US has 1% of
the world's refugees.

00:10:12.220 --> 00:10:14.290
Europe has 6% of the
world's refugees.

00:10:14.290 --> 00:10:17.110
88% of the world's refugees are
in poor or lower middle income

00:10:17.110 --> 00:10:18.350
countries.

00:10:18.350 --> 00:10:21.310
So Lebanon has 1 and
1/2 million refugees.

00:10:21.310 --> 00:10:23.980
Jordan has probably
800,000 refugees.

00:10:23.980 --> 00:10:26.110
Kenya has a million refugees.

00:10:26.110 --> 00:10:27.640
Ethiopia has a million refugees.

00:10:27.640 --> 00:10:32.330
Iran has 800,000 Afghans who
have been there for 30 years.

00:10:32.330 --> 00:10:37.060
And so the phenomenon
of global responsibility

00:10:37.060 --> 00:10:40.840
is in the mean exercised
by poor countries and lower

00:10:40.840 --> 00:10:43.060
middle income countries,
not by rich countries.

00:10:43.060 --> 00:10:45.730
And it's countries like
Bangladesh, which is

00:10:45.730 --> 00:10:48.130
fragile in all sorts of ways--

00:10:48.130 --> 00:10:51.310
it's got massive population
that's growing fast.

00:10:51.310 --> 00:10:54.430
It's just had 900,000
Rohingya Muslims arrive

00:10:54.430 --> 00:10:58.560
from Myanmar next door in
the space of six months.

00:10:58.560 --> 00:11:01.560
And the minute you start doing
the maths about what would it

00:11:01.560 --> 00:11:05.190
mean for a country like this if
that kind of numbers of people

00:11:05.190 --> 00:11:09.270
if it was proportioned up,
you'd see the kind of challenge

00:11:09.270 --> 00:11:11.610
that it poses even for a
country like Bangladesh which

00:11:11.610 --> 00:11:13.380
is doing the right
thing and opened

00:11:13.380 --> 00:11:16.890
its doors to those refugees.

00:11:16.890 --> 00:11:18.720
Jordan, which is the
second closest ally

00:11:18.720 --> 00:11:21.060
of the US in the Middle East--

00:11:21.060 --> 00:11:25.200
its debt to GDP ratio
has gone from 50% to 90%.

00:11:25.200 --> 00:11:28.505
It's the resource stress
on its water supplies

00:11:28.505 --> 00:11:30.840
and other supports--
schools, its hospitals--

00:11:30.840 --> 00:11:32.510
massively increased.

00:11:32.510 --> 00:11:34.620
And there isn't
yet a response that

00:11:34.620 --> 00:11:36.442
gives Jordan or
countries like it

00:11:36.442 --> 00:11:37.650
the kind of support it needs.

00:11:37.650 --> 00:11:40.830
And what I argue in the
book is that this crisis

00:11:40.830 --> 00:11:44.100
is manageable but
only if we change

00:11:44.100 --> 00:11:45.810
the way that we manage it.

00:11:45.810 --> 00:11:48.440
And that means shifting
our focus from the fiction

00:11:48.440 --> 00:11:51.040
that there's a short-term
problem of survival

00:11:51.040 --> 00:11:54.000
and recognize this is
a long-term challenge

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:57.070
of helping people thrive
rather than just survive.

