00:12:04.440 --> 00:12:09.960
is one of the most beloved
nonprofits by our employees,

00:12:09.960 --> 00:12:10.560
by Googlers.

00:12:10.560 --> 00:12:13.290
We have more than
5,000 Googlers who

00:12:13.290 --> 00:12:15.900
are personal donors to the IRC.

00:12:15.900 --> 00:12:21.150
So I think there's increasing
the commitment and engagement

00:12:21.150 --> 00:12:25.980
of just everyday folks,
Googlers or not, and donations.

00:12:25.980 --> 00:12:28.230
As a company, we've also
been thinking about--

00:12:28.230 --> 00:12:31.020
so we've donated, I think,
about $6 million to the IRC

00:12:31.020 --> 00:12:32.460
as Google.org.

00:12:32.460 --> 00:12:34.650
And we've also been
thinking about how can we

00:12:34.650 --> 00:12:36.180
take the best of who we are?

00:12:36.180 --> 00:12:39.270
How can we take
our tech expertise?

00:12:39.270 --> 00:12:41.220
You all saw the
video about info hub.

00:12:41.220 --> 00:12:43.920
That's an example of how
we're thinking about that.

00:12:43.920 --> 00:12:48.510
But David, you're speaking
here to this audience.

00:12:48.510 --> 00:12:50.685
What do we need to know?

00:12:50.685 --> 00:12:53.364
What do we need to hear
about how we can best

00:12:53.364 --> 00:12:54.780
support the work
that you're doing

00:12:54.780 --> 00:12:57.832
either as Google or as other
folks across the Bay Area?

00:12:57.832 --> 00:12:59.790
DAVID MILIBAND: The nice
thing about being here

00:12:59.790 --> 00:13:02.220
is that I can in person say
thank you to those of you who

00:13:02.220 --> 00:13:04.239
have stepped up to support us.

00:13:04.239 --> 00:13:06.030
And the most important
thing I can say both

00:13:06.030 --> 00:13:07.655
to those who are
supporting us or those

00:13:07.655 --> 00:13:10.550
who are thinking
about it is something

00:13:10.550 --> 00:13:12.510
that I hope you
believe, which is

00:13:12.510 --> 00:13:15.120
that you come to believe
through discussions like this

00:13:15.120 --> 00:13:16.920
that actually you can
make a difference.

00:13:16.920 --> 00:13:18.790
Although this is
a global problem,

00:13:18.790 --> 00:13:23.160
it is susceptible to
local individual response.

00:13:23.160 --> 00:13:25.570
And just to pick out a
couple of aspects to it--

00:13:25.570 --> 00:13:27.510
one thing is genuinely
unique about the IRC.

00:13:27.510 --> 00:13:30.540
We are both an international
humanitarian aid organization

00:13:30.540 --> 00:13:33.840
and a local resettlement agency.

00:13:33.840 --> 00:13:37.380
So a refugee who's given
permission to come to the US--

00:13:37.380 --> 00:13:38.570
we meet them at the airport.

00:13:38.570 --> 00:13:39.840
We get their kids into school.

00:13:39.840 --> 00:13:42.070
We help them on the
track to employment.

00:13:42.070 --> 00:13:42.990
You've been there?

00:13:42.990 --> 00:13:43.630
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:13:43.630 --> 00:13:44.370
DAVID MILIBAND:
You're a refugee?

00:13:44.370 --> 00:13:44.940
AUDIENCE: Yes, I am.

00:13:44.940 --> 00:13:46.436
DAVID MILIBAND: Where
are you a refugee from?

00:13:46.436 --> 00:13:47.936
AUDIENCE: I worked
for IRC in Bosnia

00:13:47.936 --> 00:13:49.129
during the Bosnia conflict.

00:13:49.129 --> 00:13:51.420
DAVID MILIBAND: Can we hear
him, or does he need a mic?

00:13:51.420 --> 00:13:52.880
AUDIENCE: Do you need me
to stand up over here?

00:13:52.880 --> 00:13:54.630
DAVID MILIBAND: Well,
you are standing up.

00:13:56.647 --> 00:13:58.147
AUDIENCE: Good
afternoon, everybody.

00:13:58.147 --> 00:14:01.957
My name is [INAUDIBLE].

00:14:01.957 --> 00:14:03.540
DAVID MILIBAND: Do
you work at Google?

00:14:03.540 --> 00:14:04.081
AUDIENCE: No.

00:14:04.081 --> 00:14:07.350
Actually, I arrived in San
Francisco as a refugee.

00:14:07.350 --> 00:14:09.630
I arrived at the SFO.

00:14:09.630 --> 00:14:12.180
As David said, there were
three IRC representatives

00:14:12.180 --> 00:14:16.471
waiting for me 27 years ago.

00:14:16.471 --> 00:14:17.350
I came here.

00:14:17.350 --> 00:14:21.980
We settled, lived in [INAUDIBLE]
for about eight years.

00:14:21.980 --> 00:14:25.090
[INAUDIBLE] was the first spot.

00:14:25.090 --> 00:14:28.500
Got a job in a week with the
help of IRC and Silicon Valley,

00:14:28.500 --> 00:14:33.480
worked for PRI and
Intel for years.

00:14:33.480 --> 00:14:36.010
After learning the scopes of--

00:14:36.010 --> 00:14:39.440
as you said, there's no
way to go back to Bosnia,

00:14:39.440 --> 00:14:43.600
because it was a mess
until almost the '90s.

00:14:43.600 --> 00:14:47.760
Make a permanent residency here,
between a US citizen in 2000,

00:14:47.760 --> 00:14:49.180
got married here.

00:14:49.180 --> 00:14:51.300
My kid is born here.

00:14:51.300 --> 00:14:53.250
We still go back to
Bosnia every other year.

00:14:53.250 --> 00:14:53.820
We visit.

00:14:53.820 --> 00:14:54.570
My mom's there.

00:14:54.570 --> 00:14:56.320
My family's there.

00:14:56.320 --> 00:15:00.700
By me being here, I
provide support for them.

00:15:00.700 --> 00:15:02.173
And that was the original idea.

00:15:02.173 --> 00:15:04.410
When I left IRC--

00:15:04.410 --> 00:15:08.395
Sarajevo and IRC
[INAUDIBLE] office in 1994.

00:15:08.395 --> 00:15:11.140
So the idea was
to come somewhere

00:15:11.140 --> 00:15:15.300
where it's better to get
an opportunity to thrive.

00:15:15.300 --> 00:15:18.730
I was 22 years old when I came.

00:15:18.730 --> 00:15:24.243
So long story short, I'm still
here with a Oakland commute

00:15:24.243 --> 00:15:27.936
to cross the Bay Bridge
every day as most of you do.

00:15:27.936 --> 00:15:33.810
I'm trying to help and a big
advocate of IRC for years.

00:15:33.810 --> 00:15:36.900
I can generally
say if you really

00:15:36.900 --> 00:15:41.770
want to get involved locally,
Oakland office is great.

00:15:41.770 --> 00:15:44.000
They really do
need help to teach

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:48.540
good English, to teach people
how to go to a grocery store.

00:15:48.540 --> 00:15:51.000
You can pick the car and
drive them around for one day.

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:52.080
You can learn a
different culture.

00:15:52.080 --> 00:15:54.080
Believe me, you're going
to have some good food.

00:15:57.110 --> 00:16:00.290
I help as much as I can.

00:16:00.290 --> 00:16:01.030
I know Karen.

00:16:01.030 --> 00:16:02.500
I know Maggie.

00:16:02.500 --> 00:16:04.426
I know Samir.

00:16:04.426 --> 00:16:07.480
Samir and I used to
work together years ago.

00:16:07.480 --> 00:16:10.890
Mark Bartolini is a very
good friend of mine.

00:16:10.890 --> 00:16:14.789
So I do help locally as
much as their kindness.

00:16:14.789 --> 00:16:16.830
DAVID MILIBAND: I promise
you that is not staged.

00:16:16.830 --> 00:16:18.359
But really, thank you for that.

00:16:21.160 --> 00:16:24.180
What you have said far more
eloquently than I could

00:16:24.180 --> 00:16:27.460
is that one of the great
things about the IRC

00:16:27.460 --> 00:16:29.280
is it works across
the arc of crisis.

00:16:29.280 --> 00:16:32.250
It's got a bird's-eye view from
the war zone to the neighboring

00:16:32.250 --> 00:16:35.220
state to the refugee transit
route to the lucky few getting

00:16:35.220 --> 00:16:36.510
resettled here.

00:16:36.510 --> 00:16:42.630
But I can say to you in Oakland,
in Sacramento, in San Jose,

00:16:42.630 --> 00:16:46.920
in Turlock, you can volunteer
to make a difference

00:16:46.920 --> 00:16:47.977
to someone's life.

00:16:47.977 --> 00:16:50.060
And if you want to make
the world better, doing it

00:16:50.060 --> 00:16:51.920
one life at a time is
a good place to start.

00:16:51.920 --> 00:16:55.717
So the first thing is to say
the refugee crisis doesn't

00:16:55.717 --> 00:16:56.550
have to be far away.

00:16:56.550 --> 00:16:58.230
It can be close by.

00:16:58.230 --> 00:17:00.460
The second thing that
I think is important--

00:17:00.460 --> 00:17:04.619
today, five Googlers
are in Jordan

00:17:04.619 --> 00:17:10.230
helping turn that refugee
info into a platform

00:17:10.230 --> 00:17:12.804
that refugees in Jordan across
the Middle East can use.

00:17:12.804 --> 00:17:14.220
And they're there
for three weeks.

00:17:14.220 --> 00:17:15.990
They're working with our teams.

00:17:15.990 --> 00:17:20.970
So we bring the humanitarian
expertise or our teams

00:17:20.970 --> 00:17:24.366
do, you bring the
technological expertise.

00:17:24.366 --> 00:17:25.740
We don't say
there's a technology

00:17:25.740 --> 00:17:27.420
solution to every problem.

00:17:27.420 --> 00:17:31.122
But it is very, very striking
like you heard on the video

00:17:31.122 --> 00:17:32.580
that the first
thing a refugee will

00:17:32.580 --> 00:17:34.436
do if they land in
Greece or anywhere else

00:17:34.436 --> 00:17:36.060
is they'll take their
mobile phone out.

00:17:36.060 --> 00:17:38.460
And they'll often
ask, where am I?

00:17:38.460 --> 00:17:44.040
And so the work that's going
on that is really valuable.

00:17:44.040 --> 00:17:45.315
I had the number.

00:17:45.315 --> 00:17:47.730
It said on the screen
that it was 180,000.

00:17:47.730 --> 00:17:51.300
I thought it was 800,000 who
had used the refugee info.

00:17:51.300 --> 00:17:54.300
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:17:54.300 --> 00:17:57.430
DAVID MILIBAND: Since the video,
hundreds of thousands of people

00:17:57.430 --> 00:17:59.760
have used and
benefited from that.

00:17:59.760 --> 00:18:03.870
And this is going to sound
like a really hokey point

00:18:03.870 --> 00:18:06.630
to technology--

00:18:06.630 --> 00:18:10.230
so my first question when
I went onto this site

00:18:10.230 --> 00:18:11.770
was, it's a bit dark.

00:18:11.770 --> 00:18:12.810
Why is it so dark?

00:18:12.810 --> 00:18:13.500
JACQUELLINE FULLER:
It's not very pretty

00:18:13.500 --> 00:18:14.300
DAVID MILIBAND: It's not pretty.

00:18:14.300 --> 00:18:14.800
It's dark.

00:18:14.800 --> 00:18:17.177
JACQUELLINE FULLER:
But boy, it loads fast.

00:18:17.177 --> 00:18:19.260
DAVID MILIBAND: The answer
was an interesting one,

00:18:19.260 --> 00:18:21.630
because it speaks to
the thoughtfulness that

00:18:21.630 --> 00:18:22.560
went into it.

00:18:22.560 --> 00:18:24.060
Well, we don't want
it to be pretty,

00:18:24.060 --> 00:18:25.476
and we don't want
it to be bright.

00:18:25.476 --> 00:18:28.470
Because we want it to
use up much less battery.

00:18:28.470 --> 00:18:29.130
Sorry to say.

00:18:29.130 --> 00:18:31.860
It's kind of an obvious
point, but to me it

00:18:31.860 --> 00:18:33.024
wasn't an obvious point.

00:18:33.024 --> 00:18:34.440
There's real
thoughtfulness that's

00:18:34.440 --> 00:18:38.185
gone into making sure this
is the most valuable resource

00:18:38.185 --> 00:18:38.810
for the people.

00:18:38.810 --> 00:18:40.230
So that's the second thing.

00:18:40.230 --> 00:18:44.820
Thirdly, last fiscal year we
raised $1.8 million dollars

00:18:44.820 --> 00:18:48.560
thanks to Google employees
committing and Google.org

00:18:48.560 --> 00:18:49.110
matching.

00:18:49.110 --> 00:18:51.526
I think it was a one to one
match or possible a two to one

00:18:51.526 --> 00:18:52.080
match.

00:18:52.080 --> 00:18:54.970
So that makes a
difference as well,

00:18:54.970 --> 00:18:59.220
because we know that we can
vaccinate a child for $50.

00:18:59.220 --> 00:19:04.530
We know that we can run a
women's center for $2,500.

00:19:04.530 --> 00:19:06.960
We know that we can
make a big difference

00:19:06.960 --> 00:19:10.120
for small sums of money as long
as many people are part of it.

00:19:10.120 --> 00:19:12.510
And so the fact the Google
community has invested

00:19:12.510 --> 00:19:14.110
like that I think is important.

00:19:14.110 --> 00:19:16.170
The final thing that
I would just say

00:19:16.170 --> 00:19:18.317
is a plea for you
to use your voice.

00:19:18.317 --> 00:19:19.650
Use your voice with your family.

00:19:19.650 --> 00:19:21.108
Use your voice with
your neighbors.

00:19:21.108 --> 00:19:23.700
Use your voice with your
congressman or woman,

00:19:23.700 --> 00:19:26.130
because there is a
campaign of demonization

00:19:26.130 --> 00:19:28.890
against these people
that is completely

00:19:28.890 --> 00:19:33.390
the 180 degree opposite
of what the reality is.

00:19:33.390 --> 00:19:35.430
The reality is they're
fleeing from terror,

00:19:35.430 --> 00:19:38.790
and the tragedy is they're
being branded as terrorists.

00:19:38.790 --> 00:19:40.800
And it's harder to get
to the US as a refugee

00:19:40.800 --> 00:19:42.660
than through any other route.

00:19:42.660 --> 00:19:44.700
It takes 18 to 24 months.

00:19:44.700 --> 00:19:47.520
I don't know if in the '90s, but
now there's biometric testing.

00:19:47.520 --> 00:19:48.830
Maybe even then there was.

00:19:48.830 --> 00:19:52.410
AUDIENCE: At the time, all of
the process was done overseas.

00:19:52.410 --> 00:19:54.620
So I had to go to an
interview with IRC.

00:19:54.620 --> 00:19:59.340
DAVID MILIBAND: Interviews--
it's a really tight system.

00:20:02.100 --> 00:20:04.820
I wouldn't have said this if
we'd be meeting last week,

00:20:04.820 --> 00:20:08.320
but I think the following
point is really shocking, which

00:20:08.320 --> 00:20:10.270
is that last year,
95,000 refugees

00:20:10.270 --> 00:20:12.310
were allowed into the US.

00:20:12.310 --> 00:20:14.950
This year the president
determined that only 45,000

00:20:14.950 --> 00:20:15.685
would be let in.

00:20:15.685 --> 00:20:17.800
In fact, his administration
is making sure

00:20:17.800 --> 00:20:19.915
that only 21,000
are being let in.

00:20:19.915 --> 00:20:21.040
But those are just numbers.

00:20:21.040 --> 00:20:21.880
I want to say this to you.

00:20:21.880 --> 00:20:23.560
And I apologize for
saying it, but I

00:20:23.560 --> 00:20:27.340
think it brings it
into stark perspective.

00:20:27.340 --> 00:20:30.840
More Syrians were
killed on Saturday night

00:20:30.840 --> 00:20:34.090
in a chemical weapons attack
than had been let into the US

00:20:34.090 --> 00:20:36.360
in the whole of
this fiscal year.

00:20:36.360 --> 00:20:39.130
44 Syrians have been
allowed into the US

00:20:39.130 --> 00:20:42.400
since October the 1st, 2017.

00:20:42.400 --> 00:20:45.830
11 have been allowed
into California

00:20:45.830 --> 00:20:48.660
compared to 680 that were let
in in the whole of last year

00:20:48.660 --> 00:20:49.430
to California--

00:20:49.430 --> 00:20:53.900
I think 1,800 across
the US for Syrians.

00:20:53.900 --> 00:20:56.660
So there's a real
moment of crisis

00:20:56.660 --> 00:21:00.530
where your voice is going
to decide whether or not

00:21:00.530 --> 00:21:03.020
this bipartisan US
program-- remember,

00:21:03.020 --> 00:21:05.960
it was Ronald Reagan who let in
more refugees than any other US

00:21:05.960 --> 00:21:10.630
president-- whether this
bipartisan program goes away,

00:21:10.630 --> 00:21:13.670
is slowly and silent strangled
or whether it has the chance

00:21:13.670 --> 00:21:15.632
to carry on making a
difference to the country.

00:21:15.632 --> 00:21:17.632
JACQUELLINE FULLER: I
think part of the solution

00:21:17.632 --> 00:21:20.780
is making sure that people
understand how important

00:21:20.780 --> 00:21:22.290
the contribution of refugees.

00:21:22.290 --> 00:21:26.770
And sir, your story of how
you came, and now you're

00:21:26.770 --> 00:21:30.170
a prominent integrated
member of society giving

00:21:30.170 --> 00:21:32.300
back, great community member--

00:21:32.300 --> 00:21:35.240
I know our team went
to volunteer actually

00:21:35.240 --> 00:21:37.604
at the IRC center in Oakland.

00:21:37.604 --> 00:21:39.020
And something I
learned personally

00:21:39.020 --> 00:21:40.520
from that experience--
we were doing

00:21:40.520 --> 00:21:44.600
a little bit of going
over resumes and practice

00:21:44.600 --> 00:21:45.250
interviews.

00:21:45.250 --> 00:21:48.740
And one of the things I
learned is how cultural it is.

00:21:48.740 --> 00:21:52.400
In America, you know that
you brag in a job interview,

00:21:52.400 --> 00:21:55.650
and you put your best
foot forward and what not.

00:21:55.650 --> 00:21:59.450
But in some cultures,
that's offense.

00:21:59.450 --> 00:22:02.780
And you want to be very humble
and underplay your skill

00:22:02.780 --> 00:22:04.440
set as you go into an interview.

00:22:04.440 --> 00:22:06.680
So it was interesting
just as someone

00:22:06.680 --> 00:22:08.720
who has been around the
issue for a long time,

00:22:08.720 --> 00:22:10.790
but getting
personally involved, I

00:22:10.790 --> 00:22:13.100
think, helps me get
more passionate about it

00:22:13.100 --> 00:22:15.020
but also understand some things.

00:22:15.020 --> 00:22:17.580
So for our Googlers-- for
our employees-- anyone who

00:22:17.580 --> 00:22:20.600
is interested in
volunteering with IRC,

00:22:20.600 --> 00:22:23.600
make sure you go to
go volunteer profile.

00:22:23.600 --> 00:22:26.180
Let us know about your skills,
your passions, your interests,

00:22:26.180 --> 00:22:28.880
and that way we can connect you
with IRC and our other partners

00:22:28.880 --> 00:22:32.000
who are working on these kinds
of issues like the Jordan

00:22:32.000 --> 00:22:35.646
Project or even in
Oakland or other places.

00:22:35.646 --> 00:22:38.270
So we're going to open it up to
questions in just a little bit.

00:22:38.270 --> 00:22:43.840
So if folks want to jump on the
Dory, it's go IRC dash Dory.

00:22:43.840 --> 00:22:47.070
We'll get updated
questions from there.

00:22:47.070 --> 00:22:53.030
But is there anything that
we-- so as the Bay Area,

00:22:53.030 --> 00:22:54.890
you're at Google,
a tech company.

00:22:54.890 --> 00:22:58.850
Some of our other friends are
also stepping up from tech.

00:22:58.850 --> 00:23:01.490
Are there things
that we in particular

00:23:01.490 --> 00:23:05.810
can do as you think about
all of the products that

00:23:05.810 --> 00:23:09.980
are created here in the Bay
Area, in Silicon Valley--

00:23:09.980 --> 00:23:12.170
the services that
we're creating.

00:23:12.170 --> 00:23:15.980
If you could wave a magic
wand and say, hey, Google

00:23:15.980 --> 00:23:19.200
and other companies and other
folks with these skill sets,

00:23:19.200 --> 00:23:22.110
this is what we need you
to do, what would that be?

00:23:22.110 --> 00:23:24.020
DAVID MILIBAND:
So I think that's

00:23:24.020 --> 00:23:32.490
the revolution that was
conceived in this community

00:23:32.490 --> 00:23:38.570
and that has changed the world
in the last 10, 15, 20 years.

00:23:38.570 --> 00:23:43.190
That revolution hasn't really
hit the humanitarian sector

00:23:43.190 --> 00:23:44.870
yet.

00:23:44.870 --> 00:23:51.520
And I think we've got to be
honest and say and warn you not

00:23:51.520 --> 00:23:54.994
to try and bring a technological
solution to every problem.

00:23:54.994 --> 00:23:56.660
JACQUELLINE FULLER:
As we're wont to do.

00:23:56.660 --> 00:23:58.899
DAVID MILIBAND: Well,
I didn't say that.

00:23:58.899 --> 00:23:59.690
You might say that.

00:23:59.690 --> 00:24:02.050
I couldn't possibly comment.

00:24:02.050 --> 00:24:05.660
But there is a danger
that we try and find

00:24:05.660 --> 00:24:07.820
hard technology
solutions to things

00:24:07.820 --> 00:24:10.940
that aren't amenable to that.

00:24:10.940 --> 00:24:13.280
But with that
provisor and warning,

00:24:13.280 --> 00:24:15.230
there are things that
we really struggle

00:24:15.230 --> 00:24:20.740
with because the revolution
hasn't yet hit our sector.

00:24:20.740 --> 00:24:24.410
One obvious point-- we
work in places where

00:24:24.410 --> 00:24:26.960
connectivity isn't very good.

00:24:26.960 --> 00:24:28.910
And we are now in
a situation where

00:24:28.910 --> 00:24:31.250
thanks to [INAUDIBLE]
leadership we've

00:24:31.250 --> 00:24:34.880
got all of our
196 field sites up

00:24:34.880 --> 00:24:40.230
to the standard of
connectivity of Nairobi,

00:24:40.230 --> 00:24:43.670
which is approximately 70
kilobytes for a download,

00:24:43.670 --> 00:24:46.550
25 for an upload
whatever that means.

00:24:49.640 --> 00:24:51.860
But it's expensive for us.

00:24:51.860 --> 00:24:53.670
It's really expensive.

00:24:53.670 --> 00:24:55.630
So this business
of connectivity--

00:24:55.630 --> 00:24:59.240
it's cost, how it can
be extended, how we can

00:24:59.240 --> 00:25:02.420
help our teams work offline.

00:25:02.420 --> 00:25:05.960
That whole agenda is really
important to our financing

00:25:05.960 --> 00:25:07.460
and our sustainability.

00:25:07.460 --> 00:25:13.640
Second thing is that data
inputting and ensuring

00:25:13.640 --> 00:25:17.420
that our record keeping about
individuals, about products

00:25:17.420 --> 00:25:19.606
is really top notch
would help us a lot.

00:25:19.606 --> 00:25:21.230
One of the first
things I was impressed

00:25:21.230 --> 00:25:22.940
with about IRC when I joined--

00:25:22.940 --> 00:25:25.670
we developed our own
QR reading system

00:25:25.670 --> 00:25:27.440
for making sure that
when we were shipping

00:25:27.440 --> 00:25:29.660
medical supplies into
Syria we were able to track

00:25:29.660 --> 00:25:31.050
where they went to.

00:25:31.050 --> 00:25:34.040
Because obviously, the
business of ensuring

00:25:34.040 --> 00:25:37.030
that aid is not diverted
into the wrong hands

00:25:37.030 --> 00:25:37.830
is important to us.

00:25:37.830 --> 00:25:40.169
So the record keeping
thing isn't just--

00:25:40.169 --> 00:25:41.960
the data storage thing,
the data management

00:25:41.960 --> 00:25:45.600
isn't just about our personnel,
although that matters.

00:25:45.600 --> 00:25:47.980
if someone's sacked for sexual
harassment in one office,

00:25:47.980 --> 00:25:50.070
we don't want to rehire
them in another office.

00:25:50.070 --> 00:25:51.910
So there's a personnel
aspect to it.

00:25:51.910 --> 00:25:55.530
But there's also
nutritional information

00:25:55.530 --> 00:25:57.870
on some of our patients.

00:25:57.870 --> 00:26:01.350
We help 360,000 patients
in the southwest of Syria

00:26:01.350 --> 00:26:02.110
at the moment.

00:26:02.110 --> 00:26:04.320
We want to make sure that
we're able to do that

00:26:04.320 --> 00:26:08.700
in an effective way, so
there's a whole data management

00:26:08.700 --> 00:26:10.519
aspect to it.

00:26:10.519 --> 00:26:12.810
The third thing that I think
we're not very good at yet

00:26:12.810 --> 00:26:14.393
and where you might
be able to help us

00:26:14.393 --> 00:26:16.920
is on knowledge management.

00:26:16.920 --> 00:26:19.620
We run a really fantastic-- one
of the things I'm most proud of

00:26:19.620 --> 00:26:21.540
is our outcomes and
evidence framework.

00:26:21.540 --> 00:26:22.950
We're very hard headed.

00:26:22.950 --> 00:26:26.610
We say every program has to fit
into our outcomes framework.

00:26:26.610 --> 00:26:29.100
All our programs should become
evidence-based or evidence

00:26:29.100 --> 00:26:29.640
generating.

00:26:29.640 --> 00:26:35.100
If you type in IRC outcomes and
evidence framework to Google--

00:26:35.100 --> 00:26:37.020
I'm not just saying
that because I'm here--

00:26:37.020 --> 00:26:40.440
but if you type it
in, you'll be guided

00:26:40.440 --> 00:26:43.284
through what our
field managers can see

00:26:43.284 --> 00:26:45.200
and how they should be
addressing the problem.

00:26:45.200 --> 00:26:48.070
But how we manage the
knowledge behind that,

00:26:48.070 --> 00:26:49.800
how we manage the
experience behind that

00:26:49.800 --> 00:26:52.902
we don't do well
enough at the moment.

00:26:52.902 --> 00:26:54.360
And so those are
the kind of things

00:26:54.360 --> 00:26:56.490
where I think you
could be helping us

00:26:56.490 --> 00:26:59.580
with the distinctive
technological skills

00:26:59.580 --> 00:27:00.080
you've got.

00:27:00.080 --> 00:27:02.413
One other thing which came
up when I went to the Oakland

00:27:02.413 --> 00:27:03.420
office yesterday--

00:27:03.420 --> 00:27:06.270
we haven't done a good
job on our alumni.

00:27:06.270 --> 00:27:08.710
I'd love to do an
alumni project with you.

00:27:08.710 --> 00:27:12.060
We resettled last
year 15,000 people.

00:27:12.060 --> 00:27:14.130
We've been resettling
refugees in America

00:27:14.130 --> 00:27:16.890
for the last 40 or 50 years.

00:27:16.890 --> 00:27:20.100
Andy Grove was a
resettled refugee

00:27:20.100 --> 00:27:23.550
by the IRC, which is
pretty extraordinary.

00:27:23.550 --> 00:27:24.780
His name was András Gróf.

00:27:24.780 --> 00:27:30.610
He was a Hungarian refugee.

00:27:30.610 --> 00:27:34.050
We got him into the City
College of New York in 1957.

00:27:34.050 --> 00:27:35.640
We bought him his
first hearing aid,

00:27:35.640 --> 00:27:37.880
because he'd had
rheumatic fever as a child

00:27:37.880 --> 00:27:39.630
and had never been diagnosed.

00:27:39.630 --> 00:27:42.760
And the rest is history.

00:27:42.760 --> 00:27:47.490
But we've not got a good
alumni records, even locally.

00:27:47.490 --> 00:27:49.072
So there's all sorts
of ways I would

00:27:49.072 --> 00:27:51.030
guess in which the
combination of your interest

00:27:51.030 --> 00:27:52.957
and your skills might
be able to help us.

00:27:52.957 --> 00:27:54.040
JACQUELLINE FULLER: Super.

00:27:54.040 --> 00:27:54.539
OK.

00:27:54.539 --> 00:27:57.180
Well, why don't we open up
to the room for questions?

00:27:57.180 --> 00:28:01.020
And we can also take some from
the Dory for our live stream

00:28:01.020 --> 00:28:02.322
folks.

00:28:02.322 --> 00:28:03.030
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:28:03.030 --> 00:28:04.800
Thanks very much.

00:28:04.800 --> 00:28:06.032
Excellent talk.

00:28:06.032 --> 00:28:07.300
My name's Scott Campbell.

00:28:07.300 --> 00:28:09.690
I work with the UN
Human Rights Office,

00:28:09.690 --> 00:28:12.200
usually based in central
Africa or in Geneva

00:28:12.200 --> 00:28:13.377
at our headquarters.

00:28:13.377 --> 00:28:15.210
And first of all, thank
you for the comments

00:28:15.210 --> 00:28:17.790
on immigrants' rights
and how they're

00:28:17.790 --> 00:28:18.920
being demonized these days.

00:28:18.920 --> 00:28:21.020
It's something our
commissioner for human rights

00:28:21.020 --> 00:28:24.064
feels very strongly about
and is very outspoken about.

00:28:24.064 --> 00:28:28.720
It's super important that IRC
also is taking that stand.

00:28:28.720 --> 00:28:30.640
My question-- I'm just visiting.

00:28:30.640 --> 00:28:34.350
I'm fascinated by the way that
IRC has captured technology

00:28:34.350 --> 00:28:35.976
for promoting humanitarian work.

00:28:35.976 --> 00:28:37.660
The question I'm
looking at while I'm

00:28:37.660 --> 00:28:40.870
visiting San Francisco is
how technology can be used

00:28:40.870 --> 00:28:42.220
to promote human rights work--

00:28:42.220 --> 00:28:44.380
how we can use it as
the Human Rights Office

00:28:44.380 --> 00:28:47.980
in the United Nations to
better protect and promote

00:28:47.980 --> 00:28:48.530
human rights.

00:28:48.530 --> 00:28:52.870
And I think your point,
David, [INAUDIBLE]..

00:28:52.870 --> 00:28:54.250
There's not a
technology solution

00:28:54.250 --> 00:28:58.240
for every problem is one we've
learned early on in the game.

00:28:58.240 --> 00:29:01.660
But that said, I think IRC
is far ahead of the UN Human

00:29:01.660 --> 00:29:04.410
Rights Office in how
you have carefully

00:29:04.410 --> 00:29:08.010
developed with Google some
tools that have worked well.

00:29:08.010 --> 00:29:10.870
Do you have any lessons
learned or thoughts

00:29:10.870 --> 00:29:14.220
on how technology could be
used in a human rights context

00:29:14.220 --> 00:29:15.790
rather than a humanitarian one?

00:29:15.790 --> 00:29:17.889
Thank you.

00:29:17.889 --> 00:29:20.180
JACQUELLINE FULLER: I would
say number one very humbly,

00:29:20.180 --> 00:29:22.760
I think one of the biggest
mistakes we in the tech

00:29:22.760 --> 00:29:25.370
industry tend to do
is develop solutions

00:29:25.370 --> 00:29:27.320
in our nice little
conference room

00:29:27.320 --> 00:29:29.990
here with catered food and
whatnot that don't actually

00:29:29.990 --> 00:29:32.570
work on the front line-- so I
think starting with partners

00:29:32.570 --> 00:29:36.380
like yourself, like IRC who are
on the front lines who really

00:29:36.380 --> 00:29:37.280
understand the needs.

00:29:37.280 --> 00:29:40.100
And then I think the other
thing that the teams did well

00:29:40.100 --> 00:29:47.600
is we actually sent folks to the
crisis areas, especially UX--

00:29:47.600 --> 00:29:52.840
user interface-- experts
to understand the needs

00:29:52.840 --> 00:29:56.400
and to understand even if
technology is a solution.

00:29:56.400 --> 00:29:58.190
So if we're talking
about direct service,

00:29:58.190 --> 00:30:02.600
I think having folks who
specialize in human-computer

00:30:02.600 --> 00:30:06.350
interaction and understanding
what the actual real felt needs

00:30:06.350 --> 00:30:10.050
are and whether or not
technology can be a solution--

00:30:10.050 --> 00:30:13.880
so I would say that particularly
for the front lines work.

00:30:13.880 --> 00:30:17.720
I think as far as advocacy
though and other ways

00:30:17.720 --> 00:30:23.600
to help those who are
leading on human rights--

00:30:23.600 --> 00:30:26.360
Alphabet, our company, has
several different groups.

00:30:26.360 --> 00:30:29.240
Jigsaw, for example,
has been working, for,

00:30:29.240 --> 00:30:32.120
example, with DDoS attack
protection for those

00:30:32.120 --> 00:30:36.390
who are on the front lines of
journalism and human rights.

00:30:36.390 --> 00:30:39.380
So there are ways that we
can think as a tech community

00:30:39.380 --> 00:30:43.610
about how we can ensure that
people's lifelines remain

00:30:43.610 --> 00:30:46.040
intact when they do
their heroic work

00:30:46.040 --> 00:30:49.657
as well on the advocacy front.

00:30:49.657 --> 00:30:51.740
DAVID MILIBAND: The UN
Commission of Human Rights,

00:30:51.740 --> 00:30:54.560
by the way, Zeid al-Hussein,
has done an outstanding job

00:30:54.560 --> 00:30:56.766
in the last four or
five years to speak up

00:30:56.766 --> 00:30:57.890
against human rights abuse.

00:30:57.890 --> 00:30:59.870
I would say that this is
an additional challenge

00:30:59.870 --> 00:31:00.661
for this community.

00:31:00.661 --> 00:31:02.846
I think Jackie is
absolutely right.

00:31:02.846 --> 00:31:04.220
You've got to have
the principles

00:31:04.220 --> 00:31:05.720
of human-centered
design if you're

00:31:05.720 --> 00:31:07.340
going to make a difference.

00:31:07.340 --> 00:31:10.310
You've got to put yourself in
the position of that client.

00:31:10.310 --> 00:31:11.770
Now, here's something
where I think

00:31:11.770 --> 00:31:15.920
is the biggest challenge
in respect of human rights

00:31:15.920 --> 00:31:19.040
abuse, which is that
it's not safe for those

00:31:19.040 --> 00:31:22.810
who are abused to report it.

00:31:22.810 --> 00:31:25.170
This is spoken as someone
who's obviously not

00:31:25.170 --> 00:31:26.390
from a tech state.

00:31:26.390 --> 00:31:30.230
If there's a way for the girl
in Northeast Nigeria who's

00:31:30.230 --> 00:31:32.870
being threatened by Boko
Haram, the woman in Congo who's

00:31:32.870 --> 00:31:34.920
having domestic or
sexual violence,

00:31:34.920 --> 00:31:37.280
the people in Douma
who are getting

00:31:37.280 --> 00:31:38.630
attacked by chemical weapons--

00:31:38.630 --> 00:31:40.370
if there's some way
of allowing them

00:31:40.370 --> 00:31:47.390
to anonymously but credibly
post in a way that can't then

00:31:47.390 --> 00:31:49.820
be tracked back either
by their government

00:31:49.820 --> 00:31:52.040
or by their husband
et cetera, I think

00:31:52.040 --> 00:31:55.149
that could be a
really important--

00:31:55.149 --> 00:31:57.440
JACQUELLINE FULLER: Witness
is doing something on that.

00:31:57.440 --> 00:32:00.320
DAVID MILIBAND: Because that is
where the impunity comes from.

00:32:02.506 --> 00:32:04.880
JACQUELLINE FULLER: You have
to be very smart, obviously,

00:32:04.880 --> 00:32:06.200
about the reporting.

00:32:06.200 --> 00:32:08.830
I think some of us
when we just use

00:32:08.830 --> 00:32:11.960
our cameras or whatnot
don't understand that there

00:32:11.960 --> 00:32:13.650
could be watermarks or whatnot.

00:32:13.650 --> 00:32:18.611
So I think Witness is someone
who's doing good work.

00:32:18.611 --> 00:32:20.985
AUDIENCE: I wanted to ask you
a question about the design

00:32:20.985 --> 00:32:23.987
challenge of resettlement.

00:32:23.987 --> 00:32:26.570
I read an article recently which
really troubled me suggesting

00:32:26.570 --> 00:32:29.220
that the UK was doing a
much worse job than Germany,

00:32:29.220 --> 00:32:32.130
for instance, in this
regard, because we give

00:32:32.130 --> 00:32:33.849
a fixed budget per refugee.

00:32:33.849 --> 00:32:40.232
And therefore, many refugees
that settled in [INAUDIBLE]..

00:32:40.232 --> 00:32:42.687
It seems like a fundamental
design challenge in an area

00:32:42.687 --> 00:32:44.651
where maybe data
analytics and insights

00:32:44.651 --> 00:32:47.106
could be brought to
bear to do a better job.

00:32:47.106 --> 00:32:49.570
What are your best practices?

00:32:49.570 --> 00:32:51.052
DAVID MILIBAND: Great question.

00:32:51.052 --> 00:32:53.390
Perfect, lovely question.

00:32:53.390 --> 00:32:59.020
The US also gives a
fixed amount-- $3,375

00:32:59.020 --> 00:32:59.800
to get resettled.

00:32:59.800 --> 00:33:01.600
And it's the same if
you're in Boise, Idaho

00:33:01.600 --> 00:33:04.180
as if you're in Oakland.

00:33:04.180 --> 00:33:07.750
And in Oakland, the security
deposit on a apartment--

00:33:07.750 --> 00:33:11.050
I probably don't need to tell
you-- cost $2,250 apparently.

00:33:11.050 --> 00:33:12.880
In Boise, it's $750.

00:33:12.880 --> 00:33:15.070
And surprise,
surprise, the issues

00:33:15.070 --> 00:33:18.250
of debt for refugees
arriving in the Bay Area

00:33:18.250 --> 00:33:25.060
are much greater than the
issues of debt arising in Boise.

00:33:25.060 --> 00:33:30.400
So one, standard
cookie cutter services

00:33:30.400 --> 00:33:32.200
don't work well in any context.

00:33:32.200 --> 00:33:33.530
You've got to personalize them.

00:33:33.530 --> 00:33:34.970
Some people have got
mental health issues.

00:33:34.970 --> 00:33:36.580
Some people have got
English language issues.

00:33:36.580 --> 00:33:38.496
You've got to try and
personalize the service.

00:33:38.496 --> 00:33:40.480
And one of our big
drivers that we

00:33:40.480 --> 00:33:42.430
have around outcomes
and evidence

00:33:42.430 --> 00:33:44.939
apply in our US programs as
well as in our global programs.

00:33:44.939 --> 00:33:46.480
If you click on--
well, actually, you

00:33:46.480 --> 00:33:48.354
can't click on the
[INAUDIBLE] at the moment,

00:33:48.354 --> 00:33:50.050
but we can find a
way of getting you

00:33:50.050 --> 00:33:51.020
the evidence of what we know.

00:33:51.020 --> 00:33:51.970
So the first thing is
you're right you've

00:33:51.970 --> 00:33:53.350
got to personalize it.

00:33:53.350 --> 00:33:56.380
Secondly, there's a
really important question.

00:33:56.380 --> 00:33:58.280
Which people should get
sent to the Bay Area,

00:33:58.280 --> 00:34:01.230
and which people should
get sent to Boise, Idaho?

00:34:01.230 --> 00:34:03.730
And at the moment, it's done
in a relatively rough and ready

00:34:03.730 --> 00:34:03.910
way.

00:34:03.910 --> 00:34:05.920
But we're doing a project
with Stanford University

00:34:05.920 --> 00:34:08.045
that I think you would be
interested in with Jeremy

00:34:08.045 --> 00:34:10.159
Weinstein and his team there.

00:34:12.886 --> 00:34:14.469
If you actually
developed an algorithm

00:34:14.469 --> 00:34:17.620
for where you deploy people,
you can get 20%, 30%,

00:34:17.620 --> 00:34:20.602
or even 40% improvements in
their chances of success.

00:34:20.602 --> 00:34:22.810
And I think they've published
an article in a journal

00:34:22.810 --> 00:34:23.601
somewhere about it.

00:34:23.601 --> 00:34:25.600
But the second thing
is, let's figure out

00:34:25.600 --> 00:34:26.560
where to send people.

00:34:26.560 --> 00:34:28.659
Even before you start
spending the money, where

00:34:28.659 --> 00:34:31.704
you send people can
make a big difference.

00:34:31.704 --> 00:34:33.120
What kind of skills
have they got?

00:34:33.120 --> 00:34:35.120
What kind of skills are needed?

00:34:35.120 --> 00:34:39.210
What kind of community is
there is really important.

00:34:39.210 --> 00:34:41.560
The third and most
important point

00:34:41.560 --> 00:34:44.004
is that while the money may
run out after three months,

00:34:44.004 --> 00:34:45.920
the problems don't run
out after three months.

00:34:45.920 --> 00:34:48.639
And so you got to see
people through for longer.

00:34:48.639 --> 00:34:51.730
And often, the
biggest challenges--

00:34:51.730 --> 00:34:53.800
they only emerge in
a post-trauma phase

00:34:53.800 --> 00:34:56.320
not in the immediate
trauma of arrival.

00:34:56.320 --> 00:34:58.360
So there's a lot we've
got still to learn,

00:34:58.360 --> 00:35:02.125
but I'm confident that
we're taking seriously

00:35:02.125 --> 00:35:03.340
the really tough things.

00:35:03.340 --> 00:35:06.180
So I was in Dallas visiting
our US office there,

00:35:06.180 --> 00:35:07.957
and a guy came up to me.

00:35:07.957 --> 00:35:09.040
He's a local psychiatrist.

00:35:09.040 --> 00:35:10.980
He's volunteering with us.

00:35:10.980 --> 00:35:13.330
It shows you that the
kind of personalisation

00:35:13.330 --> 00:35:17.636
of services that you need
is really wide ranging.

00:35:17.636 --> 00:35:20.010
JACQUELLINE FULLER: Let me
take a question from the Dory.

00:35:20.010 --> 00:35:22.750
So this is from Joseph.

00:35:22.750 --> 00:35:23.920
So how does the ROI--

00:35:23.920 --> 00:35:26.920
Return On Investment--
for tech aid

00:35:26.920 --> 00:35:28.480
compare with that
of traditional aid

00:35:28.480 --> 00:35:31.774
of basic needs such as medicine,
food, shelter, et cetera.

00:35:31.774 --> 00:35:33.190
And what framework,
if any, do you

00:35:33.190 --> 00:35:36.636
use to assess when to
deploy which type of aid?

00:35:36.636 --> 00:35:38.260
DAVID MILIBAND: Well
thank you, Joseph.

00:35:38.260 --> 00:35:40.220
It's a good question.

00:35:40.220 --> 00:35:43.010
I think the way to answer
it is to think as follows.

00:35:43.010 --> 00:35:47.830
First of all, your
category of non-tech aid

00:35:47.830 --> 00:35:49.270
needs to be broken down a bit.

00:35:49.270 --> 00:35:53.890
So for example, you mentioned,
I think, food and tents.

00:35:53.890 --> 00:35:55.820
The best thing to give
to people is cash.

00:35:55.820 --> 00:35:56.903
JACQUELLINE FULLER: Agree.

00:35:58.840 --> 00:36:01.810
DAVID MILIBAND: Which
immediately takes you back

00:36:01.810 --> 00:36:05.560
into tech questions, but
cash is an empowering,

00:36:05.560 --> 00:36:07.540
choice-based mechanism.

00:36:07.540 --> 00:36:13.060
It also has an advantage way
beyond even the most efficient

00:36:13.060 --> 00:36:15.316
food system or tent giving
or fleece giving system.

00:36:15.316 --> 00:36:17.237
Do you know what it is?

00:36:17.237 --> 00:36:18.820
No, you were saying
yeah as if I was--

00:36:18.820 --> 00:36:20.320
JACQUELLINE FULLER:
No, I'm agreeing

00:36:20.320 --> 00:36:22.150
that unconditional
cash transfers

00:36:22.150 --> 00:36:24.310
through mobile technology
are great innovation.

00:36:24.310 --> 00:36:27.220
DAVID MILIBAND: Well, the
unique advantage it has

00:36:27.220 --> 00:36:30.020
is that it brings money back
into the local community

00:36:30.020 --> 00:36:33.410
for the benefit of
the host community.

00:36:33.410 --> 00:36:39.700
The tents and the food is
usually sourced a long way out.

00:36:39.700 --> 00:36:41.140
We did a study in
Lebanon to show

00:36:41.140 --> 00:36:43.780
that for $100 of cash
that is given to refugee,

00:36:43.780 --> 00:36:46.850
$214 circulates in
the local economy.

00:36:46.850 --> 00:36:51.170
So don't just think about
as tech versus survival,

00:36:51.170 --> 00:36:53.050
I think he said.

00:36:53.050 --> 00:36:55.750
Secondly, we are running
value for money studies

00:36:55.750 --> 00:36:57.010
across different products.

00:36:57.010 --> 00:36:59.770
How much does it cost to
set up latrines in Jordan?

00:36:59.770 --> 00:37:02.650
How much does it cost to
set up latrines in Iraq

00:37:02.650 --> 00:37:03.760
even within Iraq?

00:37:03.760 --> 00:37:06.670
What's the cost of
a survivor's program

00:37:06.670 --> 00:37:10.990
for gender-based violence
versus a vaccination program?

00:37:10.990 --> 00:37:12.650
Those can raise
difficult questions,

00:37:12.650 --> 00:37:13.960
but they're worth asking.

00:37:13.960 --> 00:37:17.890
They don't fit into an easy
teach versus non-tech--

00:37:17.890 --> 00:37:20.330
I think just to give you
a really profound example,

00:37:20.330 --> 00:37:24.010
we found that
diagnosis of pneumonia

00:37:24.010 --> 00:37:27.990
was really low in the areas
that we worked among kids--

00:37:27.990 --> 00:37:29.710
20% more or less.

00:37:29.710 --> 00:37:32.920
And the way we got from a
20% diagnosis of pneumonia

00:37:32.920 --> 00:37:36.659
by parents and carers
to a 65% diagnosis--

00:37:36.659 --> 00:37:38.950
they'd been issued with
stopwatches by the World Health

00:37:38.950 --> 00:37:40.480
Organization, I think.

00:37:40.480 --> 00:37:42.340
But the carers and
the parents weren't

00:37:42.340 --> 00:37:44.470
able to count up to
the 40 or 50 or 60

00:37:44.470 --> 00:37:49.090
breaths that were meant to
be counted within the minute.

00:37:49.090 --> 00:37:52.180
So we issued a
necklace of beads,

00:37:52.180 --> 00:37:55.990
and it requires the carer
or the parent simply

00:37:55.990 --> 00:37:59.456
to flick a beat down
for every breath.

00:37:59.456 --> 00:38:01.830
And when the child's number--
and it's different necklace

00:38:01.830 --> 00:38:03.360
for different aged kids.

00:38:03.360 --> 00:38:06.430
But when the number of breaths
reaches a dangerous level,

00:38:06.430 --> 00:38:08.484
the color of the beads changes.

00:38:08.484 --> 00:38:10.150
And when the color
of the beads changes,

00:38:10.150 --> 00:38:13.130
that then tells you
what medicine to apply,

00:38:13.130 --> 00:38:16.820
and we got our detection
rate up to 65%.

00:38:16.820 --> 00:38:18.820
Now, it's not a
high-tech solution,

00:38:18.820 --> 00:38:22.692
but it's a very high
value for money solution.

00:38:22.692 --> 00:38:23.650
JACQUELLINE FULLER: OK.

00:38:23.650 --> 00:38:25.024
