00:44:53.600 --> 00:44:54.050
somebody's heart or mind.

00:44:54.050 --> 00:44:56.342
DAVID MILIBAND: Well, we have
this business radio show.

00:44:56.342 --> 00:44:58.799
I don't know how many of you
know this radio show in the UK

00:44:58.799 --> 00:45:00.760
called "Just a
Minute" where you have

00:45:00.760 --> 00:45:02.830
to speak without
hesitation, repetition,

00:45:02.830 --> 00:45:05.590
or deviation for one
minute on any subject,

00:45:05.590 --> 00:45:07.810
and then people press a
buzzer if you hesitate,

00:45:07.810 --> 00:45:09.010
repeat, or deviate.

00:45:09.010 --> 00:45:10.580
So it's a brilliant program.

00:45:10.580 --> 00:45:12.074
I'm not going to get into that.

00:45:12.074 --> 00:45:12.740
I tell you what.

00:45:12.740 --> 00:45:15.370
There's two approaches
to your minute.

00:45:15.370 --> 00:45:18.160
There are people like
me who are probably

00:45:18.160 --> 00:45:22.310
a minority of the population who
like as many facts as possible.

00:45:22.310 --> 00:45:23.970
So I'm like Mr. Facts.

00:45:23.970 --> 00:45:26.710
That would be the
way to persuade me.

00:45:26.710 --> 00:45:29.680
And so one in 3.64
billion chance

00:45:29.680 --> 00:45:32.050
of being killed by a
refugee in America.

00:45:34.587 --> 00:45:36.670
88% of the world's refugees
are in poor countries,

00:45:36.670 --> 00:45:38.520
not in rich countries.

00:45:38.520 --> 00:45:41.260
America's only taking 90,000
in a population of 25 million

00:45:41.260 --> 00:45:42.551
refugees, et cetera, et cetera.

00:45:42.551 --> 00:45:46.630
So there's a fact-based
approach, which probably is not

00:45:46.630 --> 00:45:47.740
the majority taste.

00:45:47.740 --> 00:45:50.622
Or there's is a
story-based approach,

00:45:50.622 --> 00:45:53.080
which is essentially to take
the individual story-- to take

00:45:53.080 --> 00:45:57.010
the story of a young man
born in Budapest in 1936.

00:45:57.010 --> 00:45:58.480
He has rheumatic fever.

00:45:58.480 --> 00:46:02.444
He escapes when the Soviet
Union crushes Hungary in 1956.

00:46:02.444 --> 00:46:03.360
He's helped to escape.

00:46:03.360 --> 00:46:04.550
He goes to a city
college in New York.

00:46:04.550 --> 00:46:05.440
He gets his PhD at Berkeley.

00:46:05.440 --> 00:46:07.170
He's "Time" man of
the year in 1997.

00:46:07.170 --> 00:46:09.941
And he's Andy Grover, and
he's the founder of Intel.

00:46:09.941 --> 00:46:11.690
The trouble with the
statistics approach--

00:46:11.690 --> 00:46:12.340
JACQUELLINE FULLER:
And, by the way,

00:46:12.340 --> 00:46:14.300
we could as Google
tell those stories

00:46:14.300 --> 00:46:18.880
with some of our founders
and CEOs and leaders.

00:46:18.880 --> 00:46:22.930
Google would not be who we
are without folks who have

00:46:22.930 --> 00:46:24.150
been given the opportunity.

00:46:24.150 --> 00:46:25.733
DAVID MILIBAND:
Sergei did a big thing

00:46:25.733 --> 00:46:27.925
when he turned up
at the airport.

00:46:27.925 --> 00:46:30.220
He was there at San
Francisco airport.

00:46:30.220 --> 00:46:34.480
That was a big statement.

00:46:34.480 --> 00:46:36.310
But the problem
with the statistics

00:46:36.310 --> 00:46:38.149
is that people don't
like statistics.

00:46:38.149 --> 00:46:39.690
The problem with
the individual story

00:46:39.690 --> 00:46:40.630
is that the people
can, say, oh, yeah.

00:46:40.630 --> 00:46:41.505
But that's one story.

00:46:41.505 --> 00:46:43.310
That's not the typical.

00:46:43.310 --> 00:46:49.180
So the best form of elevator
pitch is to combine the two.

00:46:49.180 --> 00:46:51.632
But really, I think all
you can do in a minute

00:46:51.632 --> 00:46:52.590
is get people to think.

00:46:52.590 --> 00:46:54.184
You can't persuade
them in a minute.

00:46:54.184 --> 00:46:55.600
You can get them
to think, and you

00:46:55.600 --> 00:46:59.050
go from thinking to
rethinking to persuading.

00:46:59.050 --> 00:47:02.200
And one of the big challenges--

00:47:02.200 --> 00:47:04.090
sorry, this doesn't
sound pretentious

00:47:04.090 --> 00:47:05.950
or finger pointing--

00:47:05.950 --> 00:47:08.890
but one of the dangers
of what you've all

00:47:08.890 --> 00:47:11.530
managed to do over
the last 20 years

00:47:11.530 --> 00:47:17.800
is that the space for thinking,
rethinking, and persuading

00:47:17.800 --> 00:47:20.510
is being squeezed
rather than expanded.

00:47:20.510 --> 00:47:23.080
And that's being
debated in Washington

00:47:23.080 --> 00:47:26.950
with Mark Zuckerberg's
performance today.

00:47:26.950 --> 00:47:31.030
But it's an irony that the
world has become quantumly more

00:47:31.030 --> 00:47:33.190
connected over
the last 20 years,

00:47:33.190 --> 00:47:36.640
but the space for people
to persuade each other

00:47:36.640 --> 00:47:40.180
has become quantumly
shrunk over the last 20

00:47:40.180 --> 00:47:41.780
years in my perspective.

00:47:41.780 --> 00:47:44.512
People are talking to
people who agree with them.

00:47:44.512 --> 00:47:46.720
They're being targeted by
people who agree with them.

00:47:46.720 --> 00:47:48.335
Politics has become
about mobilization

00:47:48.335 --> 00:47:49.960
of people who are
already on your side,

00:47:49.960 --> 00:47:52.197
not persuasion of people
who are not on your side.

00:47:52.197 --> 00:47:53.530
That's not only because of tech.

00:47:53.530 --> 00:47:55.990
I mean, in this country it's
because of campaign finances.

00:47:55.990 --> 00:47:57.240
It's because of redistricting.

00:47:57.240 --> 00:48:04.240
It's because of a range of
undemocratic dysfunctions.

00:48:04.240 --> 00:48:07.520
I don't want to sound
pompous about it,

00:48:07.520 --> 00:48:13.300
but creating democratic space
for thinking, rethinking--

00:48:13.300 --> 00:48:20.110
for hearing, thinking,
rethinking, persuading--

00:48:20.110 --> 00:48:25.630
hearing, listening,
thinking, rethinking,

00:48:25.630 --> 00:48:30.820
persuading is one of the
great challenges of the age.

00:48:30.820 --> 00:48:34.630
Because if we're
not able to exhibit

00:48:34.630 --> 00:48:37.990
those virtues of hearing
and listening and thinking

00:48:37.990 --> 00:48:41.230
and rethinking, then the central
promise of a free society

00:48:41.230 --> 00:48:42.490
is lost.

00:48:42.490 --> 00:48:46.090
And it is a extraordinary
state of affairs

00:48:46.090 --> 00:48:50.300
that 25 years after the
fall of the Berlin Wall,

00:48:50.300 --> 00:48:55.810
the countries of autocracy
and of dictatorship

00:48:55.810 --> 00:49:00.730
think that they
are the future not

00:49:00.730 --> 00:49:04.840
the countries of liberal
democracy and free thought.

00:49:04.840 --> 00:49:07.930
And the most
extraordinary thing is

00:49:07.930 --> 00:49:10.240
that many of the people who
live in liberal democracies

00:49:10.240 --> 00:49:13.640
think it's the dictatorships
that are the future.

00:49:13.640 --> 00:49:16.000
I'm going to get this
wrong, but something

00:49:16.000 --> 00:49:23.740
like 60% of under 25's
in democratic societies

00:49:23.740 --> 00:49:27.400
think China does a better job
of thinking through its policies

00:49:27.400 --> 00:49:29.254
than the West.

00:49:29.254 --> 00:49:30.920
I haven't got the
statistic quite right,

00:49:30.920 --> 00:49:32.400
but there's a book
by a man called

00:49:32.400 --> 00:49:34.480
called Yascha Mounk which
is really interesting

00:49:34.480 --> 00:49:36.610
book about the
fate of democracy.

00:49:36.610 --> 00:49:40.540
And the point is
that in some ways,

00:49:40.540 --> 00:49:42.280
the Chinese are
doing a brilliant job

00:49:42.280 --> 00:49:44.260
of being strategic.

00:49:44.260 --> 00:49:46.030
They're doing a
brilliant job at thinking

00:49:46.030 --> 00:49:49.600
over a 10, 15, 20-year
span, and they're

00:49:49.600 --> 00:49:52.330
doing a brilliant job of joining
up their different policies.

00:49:52.330 --> 00:49:53.950
Without wishing
to get political,

00:49:53.950 --> 00:49:55.575
there are plenty of
Western democracies

00:49:55.575 --> 00:49:58.480
that don't exhibit that
kind of strategic clarity

00:49:58.480 --> 00:50:02.510
over two days, never
mind two or 20 years.

00:50:02.510 --> 00:50:06.410
And so your question,
I think, leads

00:50:06.410 --> 00:50:09.010
into a really important debate--
which is obviously something

00:50:09.010 --> 00:50:11.890
for a different
occasion-- but does

00:50:11.890 --> 00:50:14.010
speak to something
that Jackie said

00:50:14.010 --> 00:50:17.560
that I think is really important
which is that the stand off

00:50:17.560 --> 00:50:21.400
in respect of refugees
is a symptom of a deeper

00:50:21.400 --> 00:50:23.250
set of a deeper malaise.

00:50:23.250 --> 00:50:26.950
And the argument in my book
is that after the Second World

00:50:26.950 --> 00:50:30.070
War, the better
treatment of refugees

00:50:30.070 --> 00:50:32.170
was a harbinger of the
peace and prosperity that

00:50:32.170 --> 00:50:34.128
would come from a different
international order

00:50:34.128 --> 00:50:35.260
after the Second World War.

00:50:35.260 --> 00:50:38.260
The danger now is that the
mistreatment of refugees

00:50:38.260 --> 00:50:40.840
is a harbinger of a
worse international order

00:50:40.840 --> 00:50:44.080
over the next generation, and
that's what together we've

00:50:44.080 --> 00:50:45.001
got to sort out.

